Benefits fraud reached new heights during the pandemic with £8.4billion overpaid by the DWP in the last financial year. In response, a crackdown on benefits claimants has commenced with the DWP monitoring social media and bank accounts of claimants they deem to be suspicious. Few people are fully aware of the powers the DWP has when investigating benefits fraud, granted to gather evidence and can include: The DWP can also show up at claimant’s work or home at any time in plain clothes. READ MORE: Carer’s Allowance to be replaced by new benefit payment - claimants could get £500 more The fraud and error probe will reportedly see thousands of claimants being approached in the coming months. Benefit fraud can be committed in a variety of ways, with the two most common methods being: Benefits fraud often results in overpayment which fraudsters could be made to pay back if they are caught alongside a range of other punitive measures. Fraudsters could be taken to court where they might be issued a fine of up to £5,000. They also run the risk of having their benefits cut for up to three years, but this is only applicable to sanctionable benefits. Sanctionable benefits include Employment and Support Allowance, Income Support, Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit. There are seven types of overpayments that the DWP look for specifically when investigating potential benefits fraud: Universal Credit hardship payments are classed as an overpayment if the funds cannot be recovered from the benefit that was in place at the time of payment. Official errors only apply to Universal Credit, Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance claims made on or after April 29, 2013. Next month many DWP benefits and payments will see a 3.1 percent increase but some economists have cautioned it will result in an actual £720 cut per year. This is due to the eroding effects of skyrocketing inflation, which will be compounded in April by tax increases and rising energy bills.